Cluster analyses of R users

Let’s start with the choosing the variables of the interest to make the clusterization of R users in Stackoverflow survey.

The continous variables for the k-means analyses are the years the respondend code or code professionally(the second variable next would be coded into the Pro or NOT Pro coders), then there a variables about the salary of the worker, that would be converted into the one variable that shows the Yearly income of the respondend in one currency. The hypothesis is that people who have more experience would gain mone money. Also, the variable of Age and Age of first code are taken into account.

The choice of categorical variables is aimed to catch difference in job characteristics : do the respondent use Opren Source technologies, containers or the difference in use of operational systems.

The variables connected to education i also could show the difference in educational level, and the sphere of major could show does the repondent came to R from the social sciences or the technical one, that involve the differences in aims of usinf the R language.

The lat set of variables i connected with the Job Satisfaction and the job conditions: work plan, place of work, work schedule(part-full time)

library(readr)
library(dplyr)
dataforproject2 <- read_csv("dataforproject2.csv")
ruser <- dataforproject2 %>% select(YearsCode,YearsCodePro,Age1stCode,ConvertedComp,CompFreq,MainBranch,Hobbyist,OpenSourcer,Employment,Country,Student,EdLevel,UndergradMajor,JobSat,JobSeek,WorkPlan,WorkLoc,OpSys,Containers,SocialMedia,Age)

# Coding the money variable(Yearly income)

ruser$money <- ifelse(ruser$CompFreq =="Monthly", (ruser$ConvertedComp)*12,ifelse(ruser$CompFreq =="Weekly",(ruser$ConvertedComp)*52, ruser$ConvertedComp))

#Converting vatibles to the needed tasks

for (var in names(ruser)[1:3]){
  ruser[[var]] = as.numeric(ruser[[var]])
}

for (var in names(ruser)[5:20]){
  ruser[[var]] = as.factor(ruser[[var]])
}

For the k-means the variables YearsCode,money,YearsCodePro,Age1stCode,Age.

library(factoextra)

According to scree(elbow) plot the optimal number of clusters in 2-3, whereas the gap statistics for main variables-years code and money shows that 6 clusters can be applied

Clusterizaton by 2 variables (YearsCode, money)

set.seed(20) 
ruserCluster <- kmeans(ruser_k[ , 1:2], 
                      3, 
                      nstart = 20 
)

ruserCluster3 <- kmeans(ruser_k[ , 1:2],
                      6, 
                      nstart = 20 
)

With the division on 3 clusters there is a one mall cluster of profesional users that gain enough money but with different code experience, the big middle class of coders with common distribution of wealt and experience, and the cluster of “hobby” people or students, they have variou experience but low money gain

fviz_cluster(ruserCluster, data = ruser_k[ , 1:2],

HIERARCHICAL: agnes - Agglomerative Hierarchical clustering algorithm

ruser_k <- ruser_k %>% filter(Age > 14)
ruser_k <- ruser_k %>% filter(Age < 81)
r.use <- subset(ruser_k, select = -YearsCodePro) 
d <- dist(ruser_k, method = 'euclidean') # calculate a distance matrix on selected variables

heatmap(as.matrix(d), symm = T,
        distfun = function(x) as.dist(x))

The heatmap shows the 2 cluster distribution

library(cluster)
hfit_ward <- agnes(d, method = "ward") # principle: minimal average distance between clusters
hfit_average <- agnes(d, method = "average") # average distance between an observation and existing clusters
hfit_complete <- agnes(d, method = "complete") # maximal distance between an observation and existing clusters
h_avg_cut <- hcut(d, k = 3, hc_method = "average")
fviz_cluster(h_avg_cut, ruser_k , ellipse.type = "convex")

h_avg_cut1 <- hcut(d, k = 3, hc_method = "ward")
## The "ward" method has been renamed to "ward.D"; note new "ward.D2"
fviz_cluster(h_avg_cut1, ruser_k , ellipse.type = "convex")

h_avg_cut2 <- hcut(d, k = 3, hc_method = "complete")
fviz_cluster(h_avg_cut2, ruser_k , ellipse.type = "convex")

library(dendextend)
dend <- as.dendrogram(hfit_average)
dend_col <- color_branches(dend, k = 3)
plot(dend_col)

#Ward
dend1 <- as.dendrogram(hfit_ward)
dend_col1 <- color_branches(dend1, k = 3)
plot(dend_col1)

dend2 <- as.dendrogram(hfit_complete)
dend_col2 <- color_branches(dend2, k = 3)
plot(dend_col2)

The dendograms shows the 2-3 cluster ditribution with the one big and similar inside cluster that is not broke with the increasinf the number of factors, whereas the small clusters are well defined and difference could be found further.The ward method of minimal average distance between clusters shows the best distribution

Mixed type data

Preparation of the data, creating the new variable of code Experts- does the respondend a professional or nor, according to the histogram more than 6 years of coding professionally can be presented as an expert

set.seed(2020) # for reproducibility

library(ISLR) 
library(Rtsne)
library(tidyverse)

ruser_c <- ruser %>% select(-ConvertedComp,-CompFreq,-YearsCode,-money)
ruser_c <- ruser_c %>% na.omit(YearsCodePro,Age1stCode)

hist(ruser_c$YearsCodePro)

ruser_clean = ruser_c %>%
  mutate( 
         isPro = cut(YearsCodePro,
                       breaks = c(0, 6, 40),
                       labels = c("Not Pro", "Pro"),
                       include.lowest = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(isPro = factor(isPro)) 

#glimpse(ruser_clean)

Gower ditance matrix

Silhouette width

sil_width <- c(NA)

for(i in 2:10){
  pam_fit <- pam(gower_dist,
                 diss = TRUE,
                 k = i)
  sil_width[i] <- pam_fit$silinfo$avg.width
}
plot(1:10, sil_width,
     xlab = "Number of clusters", xaxt='n',
     ylab = "Silhouette Width",
     ylim = c(0,1))
axis(1, at = seq(2, 10, by = 1), las=2)
lines(1:10, sil_width)

pam_fit <- pam(gower_dist, diss = TRUE, k = 3)
pam_fit$data <- ruser_clean[ , ]

So, the

  • 1st cluster :

  • 4 years code professionally(Non Pro coders), median age of the first code 15, not a developer by profession ,full-employed,not students(455, having masters degree(the top :math/statistics and natural sciences), not looking for a job, working without schedule in office on Windows(364), not using containers and using Facebook and WhatsUp for communication, median age 30.

  • 2nd cluster :

  • 3 code professionally(Non Pro coders), median age of the first code 16, developer by profession, full-employed, most from US, but many India respondents, more students than in the 1t cluster, having bachelor degree with major in the computer science, satisfied with the job, not looking for a job but open for new opportunities, having work schedule, mostly office workers(working home-333), Linux and Windows based,do not use containers, using Reddit for communication, median age 27, slightly younger than 1st cluster. Taking into account age and that many respondents have bachelor degree there can be many students aiming for the master degree.

  • 3rd cluster :

  • 10 code professionally(Mostly Pro coders), median age of the first code 14, developer by profession, using open source more active, full-time employed, fewer students than in other clusters, masters degree in computer science, slightly satisfied with the job, mostly working with schedule in office, using equally Linux, Mac and Windows, using containers more than 1st and 2nd clusters, using Twitter for communication, median age 35

Visualising the clusters

set.seed(111)
library(Rtsne)

tsne_obj <- Rtsne(gower_dist, is_distance = TRUE)

tsne_data <- tsne_obj$Y %>% # $Y is a matrix containing the new representations for the objects
  data.frame() %>%
  setNames(c("X", "Y")) %>%
  mutate(cluster = factor(pam_fit$clustering))

ggplot(aes(x = X, y = Y), data = tsne_data) +
  geom_point(aes(color = cluster))

On the cluster visualization the cluster of pro-workers is more separate from others(blue one), while 1st and 2nd are close to each other but still can be destinguished.

Totally, clusters are distributed by professional coders with more working experience in technical staff and two clusters of not so professional coders which are different in educational pattern, work schedule and satisfaction. The younger developers are more satisfied with their job, not technical-computer major cluster repondents work without the schedule, so have more frilance activity, while developers by profesion have more strict working conditions.
